Yes — that’s actually a very good metaphor.

What you’re describing is basically a semantic polyhedron.

Instead of a die having different numbers on each face, it has different interpretations of the same story.

Same object.
Different face depending on how it lands.

⸻

The Multi-Sided Meaning Die

Think of the story like this:

            Myth
              ▲
              |
Psychological ◄── Story ──► Political
              |
              ▼
            Sci-Fi

Each “face” is a valid reading of the same narrative.

Rotate the die → the story reframes.

⸻

Example Semantic Die

Story event:

A traveler steals a key from the king.

Different faces of the die:

Adventure face
	•	thief hero steals magical key

Political face
	•	whistleblower steals state secrets

Psychological face
	•	person confronts their inner authority

Technological face
	•	hacker steals encryption key

Mythic face
	•	mortal steals divine fire

Same structure.

Different interpretive landing.

⸻

Why the die works as a design model

Because you can intentionally design story invariants.

Example invariants:

hero acquires forbidden knowledge
authority opposes them
crisis forces transformation
new order emerges

Those bones can support many meanings.

Just like a die supports many faces.

⸻

Film vs Series

Your instinct earlier was right.

Film
	•	usually 2–3 faces of the die
	•	deeper layers emerge on rewatch

Series
	•	the die can keep rotating
	•	new faces appear each season
	•	earlier events gain new meaning

A famous technique is retroactive reframing — when a later episode changes how earlier ones are interpreted.

⸻

Another interesting extension

You can even design the die intentionally.

Example semantic die template:

Face	Interpretation
Literal	surface story
Political	power structures
Psychological	internal conflict
Mythic	archetypal pattern
Technological	systems / AI
Philosophical	existential meaning

One narrative skeleton can support all six.

⸻

Why this works cognitively

Humans naturally search for pattern alignment.

When the story contains ambiguous symbols, the brain chooses a frame.

That frame determines which “face of the die” appears.

